'''State Route 37''' ('''SR-37''') in the [[Northern California|northern]] part of the [[U.S. State]] of [[California]] runs 21&nbsp;miles (34&nbsp;km) along the northern shore of [[San Pablo Bay]]. It is currently built from [[U.S. Route 101]] in [[Novato, California|Novato]], through the southern tips of [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma]] and [[Napa County, California|Napa]] Counties, to [[Interstate 80]] in [[Vallejo, California|Vallejo]]. It serves as a vital connection between the four counties of the [[North Bay (San Francisco Bay Area)|North Bay Area]], north of San Francisco.

The whole of SR-37 has been proposed to be built to freeway standards since the early 1950s. However, the proposal was met with many economic and environmental obstacles, making the task all but impossible for much of the route. Notable problems included a leevee break in Vallejo which turned parts of the land around the highway into a marsh with endangered species, and a section of highway known as "'''Blood Alley'''" for its high-rate of fatal accidents.

==Route description==
Intended to run from the unconstructed [[State Route 251 (California)|State Route 251]], SR-37 begins in Novato with a junction at U.S. Highway 101 and heads northeast as a four-lane divided expressway. The route passes over the Petaluma River into Sonoma County before meeting the southern terminus of [[State Route 121 (California)|State Route 121]] near [[Sears Point]] (where the [[Infineon Raceway]] is located) at a signal-controlled intersection.

The route continues in a more easterly, then southeasterly, direction as a two-lane highway with a concrete divider (essentially a [[two-lane freeway|two-lane expressway]]) crossing [[Tolay Creek]] and proceeding through the [[Napa Sonoma Marsh]] at the northern edge of [[San Pablo Bay]]. Before the construction of the barrier in 1995, this portion of SR-37 was three lanes with the middle lane alternately serving as a passing lane for each direction. This stretch of highway was given the nickname of "'''Blood Alley'''" for its high-rate of fatal accidents.<ref name="bloodAlley">Gafni, Matthias [http://timesheraldonline.com/roadwork/ci_2843068 "'Blood Alley' Dad's crusade curbs carnage"] Vallejo Times Herald</ref> With the middle lane removed, accidents dropped dramatically, but it is not uncommon for long chains of cars to back up behind slower moving traffic.

[[Image:California State Route 37 in Novato.png|thumb|left|200px|SR-37 in Novato]] SR-37 becomes a freeway on [[Mare Island]], approaching northern Vallejo. After it crosses over the Napa River Bridge, it continues as a freeway overlapping the old highway alignment and then passing north of the old road known as '''Marine World Parkway''' (due to its proximity to the [[Six Flags Discovery Kingdom]] was which previously known as Marine World). SR-37 travels in a northeastern direction along the White Slough before turning east as it crosses over [[State Route 29 (California)|State Route 29]] and heads to its eastern terminus at I-80. In the early 1990s, the stretch between Fairgrounds Drive, which serves as the entrance to Discovery Kingdom, and Mini Drive was upgraded to a freeway. In 2004 and 2005, following over fifty years of complications, the remaining non-freeway section in Vallejo was upgraded as well.<ref name="37facts">{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist4/route37facts.htm|title=Caltrans Route 37 Improvements|accessdate=2007-03-02}}</ref><ref name="deir37">{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist4/deir37.htm|title=Route 37 Freeway Draft Environmental Impact Statement|accessdate=2007-03-02}}</ref><ref name="PAHP">Gafni, Matthias "[http://timesheraldonline.com/roadwork/ci_2843072 'Perserverance' at a high price"] ''Vallejo Times Herald''</ref>

